A strong wind blew through Collins, carrying dust and the smell of rain. We were near the grove at the edge of town, watching clouds carry heavy rain on the horizon. You turned to me and smiled. I saw you move your mouth in an attempt to speak, but a crack of thunder broke through the sky. To me all else went black. I could no longer see you, nor the trees beside us. I heard it though, like a bad dream, a branch severing itself from its resting point. It must have only lasted a moment, but in my dark it felt like minutes. Where you went I no longer knew, but a sudden light opened in my eyes.    
